{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504119"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:11:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2300"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2300"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.11,0.03,0.82,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99940"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2300","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2300"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2300"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1620"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"585"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42464"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99940"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department by ambulance following a low-energy motor vehicle accident. She was walking across the road when she was hit by a car. Her injuries are confined to her left leg, where she has sustained an open fracture. A primary and secondary survey has been performed and there are no other injuries. Her blood pressure is 140/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 18/min, and oxygen saturation 98% on room air.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is scheduled to be admitted under the orthopaedics team for urgent surgery for the open fracture. She has been prescribed intravenous isotonic saline, antibiotics, and pain relief in the interim.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be added to the immediate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral bisphosphonates","Tourniquet to left thigh","Intravenous diazepam","Intramuscular tetanus toxoid","Fasciotomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOpen fractures are at high risk of infection, including tetanus, which is caused by \u003Cem\u003EClostridium tetani\u003C/em\u003E spores entering through open wounds. \u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular tetanus toxoid\u003C/strong\u003E should be administered promptly if the person\u0027s immunisation status is incomplete or unknown, as part of standard prophylaxis for open wounds. This is a critical step in preventing a potentially life-threatening infection and should not be overlooked in the acute management of open fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasciotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is only indicated if there are clinical signs of compartment syndrome, such as severe pain out of proportion, tense swelling, or neurovascular compromise. In the absence of these findings, fasciotomy is not appropriate and may cause unnecessary harm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETourniquet to left thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated in the management of open fractures unless there is life-threatening haemorrhage that cannot be controlled by direct pressure. Routine use can obscure assessment of tissue viability and may worsen ischaemic injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral bisphosphonates\u003C/strong\u003E are used in the management of osteoporosis and are not indicated in the acute management of traumatic fractures, especially open fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous diazepam\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the standard management of open fractures. It may be used for muscle spasm or agitation in other contexts, but not as a routine intervention in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the immediate management of open fractures includes prompt administration of intravenous antibiotics, surgical debridement, and tetanus prophylaxis. Checking and updating tetanus immunisation status is a key step in preventing serious complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Tetanus immunisation status must be checked in all patients with open wounds or fractures.","Tetanus prophylaxis should be administered promptly if immunisation status is uncertain or incomplete.","Immediate management of open fractures includes antibiotics, surgical intervention, and tetanus prophylaxis."],"references":["Noordin S, McEwen JA, Kragh Jr CJ, Eisen A, Masri BA. Surgical tourniquets in orthopaedics. JBJS. 2009 Dec 1;91(12):2958-67.","US Department of Health and Human Services Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Tetanus. www.cdc.gov/vaccines/pubs/pinkbook/downloads/tetanus.pdf.","Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Epidemiology and Prevention of Vaccine-Preventable Diseases. Tetanus. https://www.cdc.gov/vaccines/pubs/pinkbook/tetanus.html","William W Cross, III and Marc F Swiontkowski (2008) \u201cTreatment principles in the management of open fractures\u201c  Indian J Orthop; 42(4): 377\u2013386."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2300"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82336"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T11:59:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T21:11:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2300"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99940"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0